Introduction
Christine L. Lambkin currently works at the Department of Entomology, Queensland Museum, Brisbane Australia. Christine does research in Entomology, Systematics (Taxonomy and Phylogenetics) and Evolutionary Biology. While collaborating with others working on spiders and beetles most of Christine's work is on the flies (Order Diptera). Her current research concentrates on the project 'Revisionary studies of Australian Therevidae.'

Projects

Projects (9)
Molecular analysis of the Australian flower beetles (Cetoniinae)
Project
Within this project we aim to create a comprehensive molecular dataset of the described Australian flower beetles (Coleoptera: Scarabaeidae: Cetoniinae), to discover cryptic species and to facilitate an integrative revisionary taxonomy. We intend to sample COI and nuclear genes.
View
  • 1 Update
Discoveries in the Australian flower beetles (Cetoniinae)
Project
Many species of Australian flower beetles are large and conspicuous. So it may appear that the group is well known - but this is not the case. As of 2017 at least a dozen species await description. There are unusual structures, such as in Phyllopodium, and untypical behaviour (eg. Diaphonia and Pseudoclithria). In addition to publications in well-known journals, like as Zootaxa, a prime deliverable is to establish a reference collection of Australian cetoniines (see www.afbrc.org). This project is a privately financed, long term study of the taxonomy and behaviour of the Australian flower beetles. Eventually the collection will be donated to the Queensland Museum, and some duplicates to the ANIC.
View
